sentences: Paul Lytton (born 8 March 1947, London) is an English free jazz percussionist.
In 1969 he began experimenting with free improvisational music, working in a duo with saxophonist Evan Parker.
He and Parker continued to work together into the 2000s; more recent releases include trio releases with Marilyn Crispell in 1996 (Natives and Aliens) and 1999 (After Appleby).

A founding member of the London Musicians Collective, Lytton worked extensively on the London free improvisation scene in the 1970s, and aided Paul Lovens in the foundation of the Aachen Musicians' Cooperative in 1976.

He played also on White Noise's pioneer electronic pop music album An Electric Storm in 1969.
He played jazz in London in the late 1960s while taking lessons on the tabla from P.R. Desai.
